n Berliner, Danny Fingeroth, Hollis Frampton, Ernie Gehr, J. Hoberman, Ralph Hocking, Ken Jacobs, Bill T. Jones, Peter Kubelka, Saul Levine, Camille Paglia, Phil Solomon, Maureen Turim, and many others—tell the story of this remarkable period. MacDonald concludes with an analysis of the pedagogical dimensions of the films that were produced in Binghamton, including Larry Gottheim's Horizons; Jacobs's Tom, Tom, the Piper's Son; Gehr's Serene Velocity; Frampton's Critical Mass; and Nicholas Ray's final film, We Can't Go Home Again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMotion picturesxStudy and teaching (Higher)xNew York (State)xBinghamton. 0aMotion picturesxStudy and teaching (Higher)zNew York (State)zBinghamton. 4aEducation : History of Education. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art History. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : Memoir. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aHoberman, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845890840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438458908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438458908/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles